{"cursor":"14306","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":". Enlarge for caption.]] The 'Edinburgh Phrenological Society' was established\n  in 1820. The central concepts of phrenology were that the brain is the organ\n  of the mind and that human behaviour can be usefully understood in\n  neuropsychological - rather than philosophical or religious - terms.\n  Phrenologists also laid stress on the modularity of mind. Phrenologists were\n  regarded as materialists - they were wary of Christian beliefs and acted - in\n  Edinburgh at least - as the midwives to evolutionary theory. Founded by the\n  lawyer George Combe, his physician brother Andrew and a close circle of\n  friends, the Edinburgh Society was the first - and foremost - phrenological\n  grouping in Great Britain. More than forty phrenological societies followed in\n  other parts of the British Isles.\n\nPhrenology was claimed to be scientific, but is now regarded as a pseudoscience.\nEarly Edinburgh phrenologists included the publisher Robert Chambers (1802â1871)\nauthor of [[Vestiges of the Natural History of Creation]] (1844), the botanist\nand evolutionary thinker Hewett Cottrell Watson (1804â1881), the distinguished\nasylum reformer William A.F. Browne (1805â1885) and the pioneer of women's\neducation and economic theorist William Ballantyne Hodgson (1815-1880). Charles\nDarwin - a medical student in Edinburgh in 1825/1827 - was much engaged in\nphrenological discussions at the Plinian Society - and returned to Edinburgh in\n1838 when formulating his concepts concerning natural selection as recorded in\nhis M Notebook.\n\nThe society transformed phrenology from being merely a materialist theory of the\nmind into a secular doctrine of healthy living with a reformist political\nagenda. Many of its early members were lawyers or doctors with an interest in\nsocial reform, a flair for interdisciplinary thinking and a generally secular\noutlook on human life.\n","linknr":208,"url":"Edinburgh_